\subsection{Execution Loop}

In WebArena, the LLM does not directly manipulate the website. BrowserGym and Playwright expose a controlled browser action space. The model receives a text observation produced from the DOM and accessibility tree. Browser actions such as clicking, filling fields, scrolling, navigating, and returning the final answer are executed by Playwright. The EC2 instance hosts the WebArena websites; the external agent runtime calls the LLM through Vertex AI and drives the browser against the hosted services.

\section{Retrieval and Ranking}

\subsection{Embedding Similarity}

Each procedure is rendered into compact searchable text and embedded with a sentence-embedding model. The current memory request is embedded in the same space. Since the embeddings are normalized, nearest-neighbor search can use inner product as a cosine-similarity score. This gives the retriever a semantic candidate set before graph, family, and failure evidence are considered.

\subsection{Hybrid Reranking}

The reranker combines several kinds of evidence rather than relying on vector similarity alone:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item \textbf{Semantic match:} whether the compact procedure text is close to the current request.
  \item \textbf{Lexical and page activation:} whether important goal words, page clues, and visible controls support reuse.
  \item \textbf{Outcome and graph support:} whether the procedure is connected to successful outcomes and relevant task metadata.
  \item \textbf{Task-family and action-structure fit:} whether the candidate procedure expects the same kind of task and the same broad action pattern.
  \item \textbf{Negative-memory penalty:} whether similar procedures previously failed and should reduce trust.
\end{itemize}

For Mind2Web, memory is accepted when the combined score reaches 0.34 and the activation signal is at least 0.04. The compressed FAISS backend uses a retrieval-first acceptance rule: it accepts a candidate when the combined retrieval score is at least 0.30 or semantic similarity alone is at least 0.28.

For WebArena, the gate is stricter because the agent is acting in a live browser. Same-family candidates require a score of at least 0.42, while cross-family candidates require at least 0.48. If the task family is incompatible, an additional mismatch penalty is applied before the memory can enter the prompt.

\subsection{Graph Score}

The relation graph is not only a visualization. It contributes directly to ranking by connecting procedures to task families, websites, action patterns, UI terms, success outcomes, and failure outcomes. A procedure becomes more reusable when it is strongly connected to the current site, task family, expected controls, and successful outcomes. It becomes less trustworthy when nearby graph evidence points to repeated failure or task-family mismatch.

\section{Procedure Abstraction and Context Compression}

\subsection{Positive Procedural Abstraction}

Raw trajectories are too concrete to reuse directly. They contain transient element ids, long DOM text, and task-specific values. The implemented memory therefore stores an abstract policy card with the task family, activation condition, evidence keywords, generalized action policy, expected answer format, and termination condition. Deterministic abstraction was used in the main Mind2Web retrieval benchmark to isolate memory performance. WebArena later required LLM-based abstraction because live tasks need better semantic generalization and clearer stopping rules.

\subsection{Negative Memory}

For failed tasks, the system stores the failure family, the bad pattern, the avoid-rule, and the penalty that should apply to similar future candidates. During retrieval, negative memories are matched against the current request and candidate procedures. If the new task resembles a previously failed pattern, the candidate receives a risk penalty before the final gate. This prevents repeated reuse of procedures that look superficially similar but previously failed.

\subsection{Prompt Context Budget}

Instead of placing full trajectories in the prompt, the prompt receives compact policy cards. The online prompt contains the current goal, current browser observation, action history, accepted procedure cards, negative warnings, and task-family rules. The memory is guidance, not a hard script: the LLM still chooses each action from the current page state.

\section{Storage and Retrieval Optimization}

\subsection{Compression}

A 384-dimensional float32 embedding requires 1,536 bytes for the raw vector values. Scalar quantization stores one byte per dimension, reducing the vector code to 384 bytes. Product quantization with 16 sub-codes stores a 16-byte vector code. Thus, IVFPQ reduces the vector-code portion from 1,536 bytes to 16 bytes, a nominal $96\times$ compression before metadata and index overhead.

The main idea is simple: exact search preserves all vector values, scalar quantization stores coarse per-dimension values, and product quantization stores compact codebook ids for vector chunks. OPQ adds a learned rotation before product quantization so the compressed codes preserve similarity more accurately.

\subsection{Index Families}

The implementation evaluates several backends:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
  \item \textbf{Flat IP}: exact inner-product search over normalized vectors.
  \item \textbf{HNSW}: graph-based ANN with $M=32$ and efSearch $=64$.
  \item \textbf{SQ8}: scalar-quantized vectors.
  \item \textbf{HNSW+SQ8}: HNSW graph over scalar-quantized vectors.
  \item \textbf{IVFPQ}: inverted-file coarse clustering with product-quantized residual/vector codes.
  \item \textbf{OPQ-IVFPQ}: learned rotation before IVFPQ to reduce quantization error.
  \item \textbf{TurboQuant-like binary rotation}: signed-permutation rotation followed by binary codes.
  \item \textbf{RaBitQ-inspired dense/binary variants}: low-bit randomized quantization experiments.
\end{itemize}

Exact search compares the query against every stored vector. HNSW avoids many comparisons by navigating a proximity graph. IVF searches only a subset of coarse clusters, and PQ makes each distance computation cheaper by using compressed codes. Binary rotation methods are even smaller because they compare sign patterns rather than full vectors, but the WebArena benchmark shows that this extra compression loses retrieval quality on the small shopping-domain memory corpus.

